WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:06.550
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:06.550 --> 00:00:09.050
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: She's
known as a writer

00:00:09.050 --> 00:00:12.290
who captures the essential
American character,

00:00:12.290 --> 00:00:13.890
not just by chronicling their lives

00:00:13.890 --> 00:00:18.670
but by letting us see
deep into their souls.

00:00:18.670 --> 00:00:22.180
We see their hopes and their
disappointments, their flaws,

00:00:22.180 --> 00:00:26.620 position:56%
their fears, and we do so amazingly,

00:00:26.620 --> 00:00:30.780
on a very highly granular
level, up close.

00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:33.490
Elizabeth's novels are
like shimmering necklaces,

00:00:33.490 --> 00:00:38.660
each chapter is a bead along
a continuum of related lives.

00:00:38.660 --> 00:00:43.510
And somehow she manages to weave
this incredible tapestry of lives,

00:00:43.510 --> 00:00:47.770
back into themselves,
in book after book.

00:00:47.770 --> 00:00:52.910
They are free of sentimentality,
they are without judgment.

00:00:52.910 --> 00:00:58.180
We see the bad and the good in
all, just as we might see the bad

00:00:58.180 --> 00:01:02.440
and the good in the
people that we love most.

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:05.660
There are no villains
here, in Elizabeth's work.

00:01:05.660 --> 00:01:12.440 position:56%
All are simply human, all have their
reasons, each has an intricate past.

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:17.790 position:56%
She's been called perceptive, deeply
empathetic, astonishingly forceful,

00:01:17.790 --> 00:01:23.110
one of America's most graceful
and grace-filled writers.

00:01:23.110 --> 00:01:28.230
She was born in Portland, Maine,
daughter of a science professor,

00:01:28.230 --> 00:01:31.530
I believe, and an English teacher.

00:01:31.530 --> 00:01:33.480
She grew up in Maine
and New Hampshire.

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:36.140
She's been a writer,
she says, all her life,

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:39.640
although she didn't publish her
first book until she was over 40,

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:43.290
giving a lot of people hope here.

00:01:43.290 --> 00:01:46.880
She spent her early years
after college as a waitress,

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:49.550
a working woman, a
law school graduate,

00:01:49.550 --> 00:01:52.980
witnessing some stark
realities about American life

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:56.690
and the very apparent
hierarchies of class,

00:01:56.690 --> 00:01:59.520
the "haves" and the "have-nots."

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:04.580
The ambitious and the vanquished,
the willful and the repentant,

00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:08.510
the leaders and the followers,
the cogs and the rebels.

00:02:08.510 --> 00:02:12.670
Somewhere along the way, because
she was a voracious reader,

00:02:12.670 --> 00:02:18.550
she acquired a keen eye
for economical language

00:02:18.550 --> 00:02:20.640
and the lyrical turn of phrase.

00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:23.030
A Strout sentence, you all know

00:02:23.030 --> 00:02:26.650
who have read her, can
contain a universe.

00:02:26.650 --> 00:02:29.680
She's given us a rich collection
of memorable books, each volume,

00:02:29.680 --> 00:02:34.370
another testimonial of her
perspective and her record

00:02:34.370 --> 00:02:36.700
of contemporary American life.

00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:40.340
You know them all: "Amy and
Isabelle" was her first,

00:02:40.340 --> 00:02:43.780
"Abide with Me," "Olive
Kitteridge," "The Burgess Boys,"

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:47.710
"My Name is Lucy Barton" and
now "Anything is Possible."

00:02:47.710 --> 00:02:54.080 position:56%
For this she's won a Pulitzer Prize,
the Premio Bancarella among others

00:02:54.080 --> 00:02:57.910
as well as being a finalist for
many other prestigious awards.

00:02:57.910 --> 00:02:59.990
Thank you so much for
joining us, Liz.

00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:01.490
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Thank you.

00:03:01.490 --> 00:03:03.510
