00:12:34.630 --> 00:12:37.900
that essay, that I remember that
that sounded familiar to me.

00:12:37.900 --> 00:12:40.830
And I went back to "Olive
Kitteridge," and there's a place

00:12:40.830 --> 00:12:46.180
where a character says, "'You
get used to things,' he thinks,

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:49.990
'without getting used to things.'"
Which is sort of the opposite.

00:12:49.990 --> 00:12:51.290
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Right.

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:52.680
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: But there's
a, there is that sense,

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:56.340
and I feel it very much in your
writing, that people are sort

00:12:56.340 --> 00:12:58.600 position:56%
of operating on a superficial level.

00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:02.580
But there is a deep, deep
human instinct beneath it

00:13:02.580 --> 00:13:04.120
that drives them.

00:13:04.120 --> 00:13:05.420
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Right.

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:06.720
But that would be most people.

00:13:06.720 --> 00:13:08.020
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Yeah.

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:09.320
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: You know.

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:10.620
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Yeah, yeah.

00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:11.920
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: I mean,
that's most of our lives.

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:14.450
I mean, we are walking
around, dealing with things,

00:13:14.450 --> 00:13:21.030
and yet we have our own internal
things that are privately ours.

00:13:21.030 --> 00:13:22.330
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Right.

00:13:22.330 --> 00:13:23.630
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: And very deep.

00:13:23.630 --> 00:13:25.020
Because they belong to us.

00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:27.000
They're who we are.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.290
And they can either
get expressed or not.

00:13:30.290 --> 00:13:32.300
And that's what interests me.

00:13:32.300 --> 00:13:35.190
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Well, one very
deep thing I think that many people

00:13:35.190 --> 00:13:40.690
in this room who are your readers,
knew instinctively and immediately

00:13:40.690 --> 00:13:45.490
when they read "Amy and Isabelle"
was that you understood something

00:13:45.490 --> 00:13:51.140
about the human condition that was
very connective and very appealing

00:13:51.140 --> 00:13:57.670
and somehow spoke truth
in a great way.

00:13:57.670 --> 00:14:02.090
Tell us a bit about how "Amy
and Isabelle," let's start

00:14:02.090 --> 00:14:03.890
at the beginning, happened.

00:14:03.890 --> 00:14:07.580
And how it came to you, and
why this mother and daughter

00:14:07.580 --> 00:14:11.770
and why this disappointment
of lost opportunity.

00:14:11.770 --> 00:14:13.070
How did that come?

00:14:13.070 --> 00:14:14.370
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Right.

00:14:14.370 --> 00:14:19.270
You know, the book -- I understood,
the book started as as short story,

00:14:19.270 --> 00:14:21.180
because that's what I
was writing at the time.

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:23.980
And nobody wanted it, naturally.

00:14:23.980 --> 00:14:28.430
So, but it kept not going away.

00:14:28.430 --> 00:14:30.150
It kept coming back.

00:14:30.150 --> 00:14:33.270
And then I finally realized,
"Okay, I'm going to write a novel,"

00:14:33.270 --> 00:14:36.540
and that was, like, so, you
know, exciting and nervewracking.

00:14:36.540 --> 00:14:40.490
And so I began with Amy.

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:43.150
I mean, I never write
from beginning to end.

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:45.850
But I thought at first it
would be mostly Amy's story.

00:14:45.850 --> 00:14:47.150 position:56%
And then I realized, no, no, no, no.

00:14:47.150 --> 00:14:49.570
This is both of their stories.

00:14:49.570 --> 00:14:51.520
And that's why's it's
called "Amy and Isabelle,"

00:14:51.520 --> 00:14:52.820
because it's both their stories.

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:55.730
So, and I realized the
mother's story was just

00:14:55.730 --> 00:14:58.080
as important as the
daughter's story.

00:14:58.080 --> 00:15:00.910
And toward the beginning
when I wrote the sentence,

00:15:00.910 --> 00:15:04.170
"but Isabelle had her own
story," then I realized, oh,

00:15:04.170 --> 00:15:05.780
I can do that, I can write that.

00:15:05.780 --> 00:15:07.370
And then I can tell that story.

00:15:07.370 --> 00:15:12.540
And so, but Isabelle was a little
