How in the world did
you enter that world?

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:36.540
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Right.

00:35:36.540 --> 00:35:38.800
And I meant it be like
a faux memoir.

00:35:38.800 --> 00:35:42.050
I mean, I meant this to
be Lucy Barton's memoir.

00:35:42.050 --> 00:35:45.150
But, how did I enter
that world when it was

00:35:45.150 --> 00:35:48.240
so different from my childhood?

00:35:48.240 --> 00:35:54.610
You know, I understood
her background somehow.

00:35:54.610 --> 00:35:57.800
I just began to really
understand it.

00:35:57.800 --> 00:36:01.050
And I went to school with a boy
-- I mention this in the essay.

00:36:01.050 --> 00:36:03.810
I went to school with a boy who
was from that kind of background.

00:36:03.810 --> 00:36:07.890
And every rural town that I've
ever known has had a family

00:36:07.890 --> 00:36:10.490
like Lucy's that's just so poor,

00:36:10.490 --> 00:36:13.730
and so odd that they're
ostracized by everybody.

00:36:13.730 --> 00:36:16.790
And there was a family
like that in my hometown.

00:36:16.790 --> 00:36:19.010
And this boy never spoke.

00:36:19.010 --> 00:36:20.310
He never spoke.

00:36:20.310 --> 00:36:21.610
And nobody ever spoke to him.

00:36:21.610 --> 00:36:23.020
And one day, the third grade
teacher said to him, "You're,

00:36:23.020 --> 00:36:24.430
you have dirt behind your ears.

00:36:24.430 --> 00:36:26.250
Nobody's too poor to
buy a bar of soap."

00:36:26.250 --> 00:36:28.800
And that kid got so red.

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:31.340
And I always remembered that.

00:36:31.340 --> 00:36:34.470
And I had a sense of what
his house looked like,

00:36:34.470 --> 00:36:36.110
because I would go
by it every so often.

00:36:36.110 --> 00:36:40.060
But anyway, so that's how I did it.

00:36:40.060 --> 00:36:41.360
I don't know how I did it.

00:36:41.360 --> 00:36:46.340
But I entered into that world
and brought her through.

00:36:46.340 --> 00:36:47.640
Thank you.

00:36:47.640 --> 00:36:48.940
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Thank
