00:36:53.690 --> 00:36:56.610
that you shred some
of your journals.

00:36:56.610 --> 00:36:59.240
And I was just curious, why would,

00:36:59.240 --> 00:37:01.070
why did you shred your,
some of your journals?

00:37:01.070 --> 00:37:04.590
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout:
Because they're so foolish.

00:37:04.590 --> 00:37:12.220
They're just, they're
so worth shredding.

00:37:14.200 --> 00:37:15.500
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:37:15.500 --> 00:37:17.030
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: It's just,
you know, one stream, whatever.

00:37:17.030 --> 00:37:18.330
Thank you.

00:37:18.330 --> 00:37:22.010
But, I mean, because I did.

00:37:22.010 --> 00:37:23.310
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Thank
you for the question.

00:37:23.310 --> 00:37:24.610
Over here, please.

00:37:24.610 --> 00:37:25.910
&gt;&gt; Hi, Elizabeth.

00:37:25.910 --> 00:37:27.210
I'm from Maine.

00:37:27.210 --> 00:37:28.510
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Oh.

00:37:28.510 --> 00:37:29.810
Where?

00:37:29.810 --> 00:37:31.920
&gt;&gt; Portland, and we have
a house in Islesboro now.

00:37:31.920 --> 00:37:36.750
One of the things that I think
you really get right, as a Mainer,

00:37:36.750 --> 00:37:40.380
is just the frugality
of all the Mainers.

00:37:40.380 --> 00:37:42.330
And I just wanted to, I think
it was in "The Burgess Boys."

00:37:42.330 --> 00:37:43.780
A brother comes home
to visit the sister.

00:37:43.780 --> 00:37:45.540
And the house is 50 degrees.

00:37:45.540 --> 00:37:46.840
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Yeah.

00:37:46.840 --> 00:37:48.140
&gt;&gt; Which is a thing.

00:37:48.140 --> 00:37:49.440
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Yeah.

00:37:49.440 --> 00:37:52.730
&gt;&gt; And then one of the themes ithat
I see in your books is the person

00:37:52.730 --> 00:37:54.840
in the family who's gotten away --

00:37:54.840 --> 00:37:56.140
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Right.

00:37:56.140 --> 00:37:57.440 position:56%
&gt;&gt; And made it, and then comes back.

00:37:57.440 --> 00:38:00.130
In "Lucy Barton," there's
some really vivid scenes.

00:38:00.130 --> 00:38:02.830
Can you talk a little
bit about that?

00:38:02.830 --> 00:38:04.130
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: You know.

00:38:04.130 --> 00:38:06.880 position:56%
I think that, and also like Jim
Burgess -- he's made it, supposedly,

00:38:06.880 --> 00:38:10.520
and then he comes back
and stumbles around.

00:38:10.520 --> 00:38:15.140
And I think that, it's just
any dichotomy that you can get

00:38:15.140 --> 00:38:16.960
on the page is interesting.

00:38:16.960 --> 00:38:19.150
And I did come from
a very small town,

00:38:19.150 --> 00:38:20.870
and I did end up living
in New York City.

00:38:20.870 --> 00:38:25.700
So that is a think that I am
familiar with: the change of going

00:38:25.700 --> 00:38:28.080
from an environment like
the kind I grew up in

00:38:28.080 --> 00:38:29.800
and then living in New York.

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:31.900
So that's interesting
to me personally

00:38:31.900 --> 00:38:33.520
because I've experienced it.

00:38:33.520 --> 00:38:37.890
But I think that, you know,
sometimes people talk about hose

00:38:37.890 --> 00:38:41.180
that have been trapped at
home, or have stayed at home.

00:38:41.180 --> 00:38:44.530
And I don't think of them as
trapped, or staying at home.

00:38:44.530 --> 00:38:45.980
I think that's simply the life.

00:38:45.980 --> 00:38:49.050
Like, you know, for
example, Susan Burgess.

00:38:49.050 --> 00:38:52.340
I always remember this woman in
New York City, she said to me,

00:38:52.340 --> 00:38:54.920
"Why didn't Susan just leave?"

00:38:54.920 --> 00:38:57.340
And it was so interesting to
me that she would ask that,

00:38:57.340 --> 00:39:00.710
because why would Susan leave?

00:39:00.710 --> 00:39:02.220
It's her home.

00:39:02.220 --> 00:39:03.880
Why in the world would she leave?

00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:07.410
So, the New York person
didn't understand that,

00:39:07.410 --> 00:39:10.390
and I found that interesting, you
know, for a number of reasons.

00:39:10.390 --> 00:39:12.120
But Susan lives her life.

00:39:12.120 --> 00:39:15.910
She's not trapped anymore than
anybody is, whether they're living

00:39:15.910 --> 00:39:19.130
in New York, or Shirley
Falls, you see.

00:39:19.130 --> 00:39:23.540
So, that's also interesting
to me, you know?

00:39:23.540 --> 00:39:25.810
&gt;&gt; And then the person who
gets away and makes it,

00:39:25.810 --> 00:39:28.170 position:56%
doesn't really get away and make it.

00:39:28.170 --> 00:39:29.470
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: No.

00:39:29.470 --> 00:39:30.770
Because nobody does.

00:39:30.770 --> 00:39:32.330
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: We only have
time for one more question.

00:39:32.330 --> 00:39:33.630
So.

00:39:33.630 --> 00:39:34.990
&gt;&gt; Hi. I love your work.

00:39:34.990 --> 00:39:36.530
Thank you for coming here today.

00:39:36.530 --> 00:39:38.750
I was wondering, you
spoke to the fact

00:39:38.750 --> 00:39:41.090
that you don't ever write
from beginning to end.

00:39:41.090 --> 00:39:42.390
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Right.

00:39:42.390 --> 00:39:44.360
&gt;&gt; And I was wondering, and
it's kind of a two-parter,

00:39:44.360 --> 00:39:47.270
if you could speak a little
bit about when you know --

00:39:47.270 --> 00:39:51.140
how the process comes about of
putting the pieces together,

00:39:51.140 --> 00:39:53.280
and whether you know the
end at the beginning,

00:39:53.280 --> 00:39:56.260
or where the end comes
to you, and how you --

00:39:56.260 --> 00:39:57.560
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Right.

00:39:57.560 --> 00:40:00.210
&gt;&gt; I'm a nonlinear writer,
and I was trying to figure

00:40:00.210 --> 00:40:01.630
out how you get those pieces.

00:40:01.630 --> 00:40:03.030
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Strout: Right.

00:40:03.030 --> 00:40:05.420
You know, I'll write in scenes.

00:40:05.420 --> 00:40:07.620
Every day I just create
different scenes.

00:40:07.620 --> 00:40:12.580
And after a while I'll begin to see
that they'll connect in some way.

00:40:12.580 --> 00:40:15.000
And so, whether it's
a story, or a novel,

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:18.820
I will understand the connection
between the scenes that have --

00:40:18.820 --> 00:40:20.470
the scenes have to
have a pulse to them.

00:40:20.470 --> 00:40:21.830
They have to be living.

00:40:21.830 --> 00:40:24.220
And if they do, then they
will begin to connect.

00:40:24.220 --> 00:40:27.460
That's why I never worry
about plot, because that's

00:40:27.460 --> 00:40:30.070
so artificially placed
onto something.

00:40:30.070 --> 00:40:34.430 position:56%
But if it arrives, you know, from
the work itself, and so I will begin

00:40:34.430 --> 00:40:36.890
to recognize the connection
between things.

00:40:36.890 --> 00:40:39.730
And then at some point, I
do have to think, "Okay,

00:40:39.730 --> 00:40:42.010
now where am I going to start?"

00:40:42.010 --> 00:40:44.160
And then I'll start to
pull it together, you know,

00:40:44.160 --> 00:40:46.510
with as tight a thread as possible.

00:40:46.510 --> 00:40:49.320
And then, the ending.

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:51.800
You know, I will have probably
already written the ending.

00:40:51.800 --> 00:40:54.660
And with the last page of
Olive Kitteridge, you know,

00:40:54.660 --> 00:40:59.850
I wrote that way before I
wrote the story, that it ended,

00:40:59.850 --> 00:41:02.370
and I just wrote that last
page, and it just came to me,

00:41:02.370 --> 00:41:05.210
and I wrote at the top,
"End," question mark.

00:41:05.210 --> 00:41:07.520
And thank God I didn't lose it.

00:41:07.520 --> 00:41:10.340
Because I easily could have.

00:41:10.340 --> 00:41:13.260
You know, I'm really
very messy, as a writer,

00:41:13.260 --> 00:41:14.890
and I could have lost
it, but I didn't.

00:41:14.890 --> 00:41:17.910
And so as I was writing
that final story, I thought,

00:41:17.910 --> 00:41:20.740
"Wait a minute, I have
the end of this."

00:41:20.740 --> 00:41:22.040
And I did!

